- A Piotroski F-score is a system to evaluate the financial health of a company; 
- A PE ratio (price-to-earnings ratio) is used to evaluate the relative cost of a stock; 
- Profitability and operating efficiency scores are indicators of how effectively a company is generating earnings from its operations.

- Piotroski F-score is a measure of a company's financial health, calculated based on nine criteria, including return on assets, cash flow return on assets, change in return on assets, and others; 
- A higher Piotroski F-score indicates better financial health; 
- Profitability refers to the ability of a company to generate earnings; 
- Industry refers to a category of companies that produce similar products or services.

- "High custom performance score" refers to a score greater than 5, calculated as the sum of profitability and operating efficiency minus half of the leverage; 
- "Recent performance metrics" include the custom score and the average closing price over the last 30 days;
- "Currently being watched" implies that these stocks are in the watchlists of users who have shown recent activity by logging in within the last 7 days.
